'''Valentín Barco''' (born 23 July 2004), better known as '''''Colo'' Barco''', is an Argentine professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Left back]] for [[Ligue 1]] club [[RC Strasbourg Alsace|Strasbourg]] and the [[Argentina national football team|Argentina national team]].

==Club career==
===Boca Juniors===
In 2021, Barco was scouted by Argentine club [[Boca Juniors]] and immediately signed his professional contract.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Germán |last=Boero |title=Valentin Barco: Boca Juniors wonderkid who could be Manchester City-bound |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/valentin-barco-boca-juniors-wonderkid-man-city/3tttyt9ahdve17qwy58nexcj8 |website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]] |date=17 August 2021 |access-date=18 August 2021}}</ref> On 16 July 2021, he made his professional debut at 16 years old in a 1–1 draw against [[Unión de Santa Fe|Unión]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Valentín Barco set to join Brighton from Boca Juniors |url=https://onefootball.com/en/news/valentin-barco-set-to-join-brighton-from-boca-juniors-38852942 |website=OneFootball |date=11 January 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Unión (Santa Fe) 1–1 Boca Juniors &#124; Final Score |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/610246/boca-juniors-union-santa-fe |website=[[ESPN]] |date=16 June 2023 |access-date=11 January 2024}}</ref>{{Better source needed|date=May 2024}} He was included in [[The Guardian]]{{'}}s "Next Generation" list for 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 October 2021 |title=Next Generation 2021: 60 of the best young talents in world football |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2021/oct/07/next-generation-2021-60-of-the-best-young-talents-in-world-football |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>

On 29 June 2023, Barco scored his first goal for the club in a 4–0 victory against [[Monagas S.C.|Monagas]] in the [[Copa Libertadores]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Boca Juniors 4–0 Monagas SC {{!}} Final Score |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/667886|publisher=ESPN |date=29 June 2023 |access-date=11 January 2024}}</ref>{{Better source needed|date=May 2024}} Less than one month later on 24 July, he scored his first league goal in a 2–1 victory against [[Newell's Old Boys]] after converting a [[Cross (association football)|cross]] from [[Pol Fernández]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Boca Juniors 2–1 Newell's Old Boys |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/commentary/_/gameId/656570|publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=25 July 2023 |access-date=11 January 2024}}</ref>{{Better source needed|date=May 2024}} He continued to fulfil his promise for Boca, when on 10 August 2023, during their game against [[Club Nacional de Football|Nacional Montevideo]] in the [[Copa Libertadores]] round of 16, produced a dominant display for the blue and gold, displaying creativity key to both Boca goals. Boca were pegged back twice during the 90 minutes of regulation play and with the game at 2–2 on the night and on aggregate, it went to penalties. Barco stepped up fifth of five for Boca and scored the decisive penalty to take them to the semi-finals.{{Citation needed|date=February 2026}}

In the semi-finals, Boca faced Brazilian club [[Palmeiras]]. The first leg finished goalless at [[La Bombonera]] in [[Buenos Aires]]. During the return leg in Brazil, Barco stood on the ball with both feet whilst in possession, a move that at his young age in a [[Copa Libertadores]] semi-final, stunned the Palmeiras players, fans and South American critics alike. It was a move that garnered many headlines, despite a counter-attacking goal by [[Edinson Cavani]] and a red card being shown to [[Marcos Rojo]].  The draw, once again for Boca – with a 1–1 aggregate score – went to a penalty shootout. They won the shootout 4–2, courtesy of a heroic display by goalkeeper [[Sergio Romero]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2026}}

At the age of 19, Barco played as a starter for Boca in the [[2023 Copa Libertadores final]] against [[Fluminense FC|Fluminense]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2026}} He played 78 minutes before being replaced by fellow youth product [[Luca Langoni]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2026}} Boca lost the final 2–1 after extra time, courtesy of goals by [[German Cano]] and [[John Kennedy (Brazilian footballer)|John Kennedy]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2026}}

===Playing abroad===
On 20 January 2024, Barco transferred to [[Premier League|English Premier League]] club [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] for an undisclosed fee – reported to be around $10 million (€9.1 million) – signing a four-and-a-half year contract until 30 June 2028.<ref>{{cite news |title=Valentin Barco joins Albion from Boca Juniors |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3861799/valentin-barco-joins-albion-from-boca-juniors |website=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |date=20 January 2024 |archive-date=16 April 2024 |access-date=20 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240416042615/https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3861799/valentin-barco-joins-albion-from-boca-juniors |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|first=Joseph |last=O'Sullivan |title=Brighton Sign Valentín Barco From Boca Juniors For $10 Million Fee |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/josephosullivan/2024/01/16/brighton-sign-valentn-barco-from-boca-juniors-for-10-million-fee/|magazine=[[Forbes]] |date=16 January 2024 |access-date=21 January 2024}}</ref> On 23 August 2024, Barco moved to [[La Liga]] club [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] on loan for the 2024–25 season without buy option.<ref>{{cite web |title=Valentín Barco, nuevo refuerzo para la parcela defensiva del Sevilla FC |url=https://sevillafc.es/actualidad/noticias/cesion-valentin-barco-sevilla-fc-2425 |publisher=Sevilla FC |access-date=23 August 2024 |language=es|date=23 August 2024 }}</ref>

On 2 February 2025, Barco moved on another loan, this time to [[Ligue 1]] club [[RC Strasbourg Alsace|Strasbourg]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-02-02 |title=Strasbourg annonce l'arrivée d'un international argentin |url=https://www.onzemondial.com/transferts/strasbourg-annonce-l-arrivee-d-un-international-argentin-941910 |access-date=2025-02-02 |website=Onze Mondial |language=fr}}</ref> On 2 July 2025, he moved to Strasbourg permanently for a fee of £7.87 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cn8656yqw4po|title=Barco seals permanent Strasbourg switch|website=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|date=2 July 2025|access-date=3 July 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
On 23 March 2024, Barco debuted for the [[Argentina national football team|Argentine senior squad]] on 23 March 2024 in a [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly match]] against [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=Nico |last=Castillo |title=Valentín Barco, el integrante número 45 de los debutantes en el ciclo del "Leónidas" |url=https://www.vavel.com/ar/futbol-argentino/2024/03/23/seleccion-argentina/1177122-valentin-barco-el-integrante-numero-45-delos-debutantes-en-el-ciclo-del-leonidas.html |website=[[Vavel]] |date=23 March 2024 |language=es}}</ref> He scored his first international goal in the stoppage time of a 5–0 victory over [[Zambia national football team|Zambia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.batimes.com.ar/news/amp/sports/messi-on-target-as-argentina-put-five-past-zambia-in-world-cup-send-off.phtml |title=Messi on target as Argentina put five past Zambia in World Cup send-off |publisher=Buenos Aires Times |date=1 April 2026 }}</ref>

==Style of play==
Barco has been described as one of Argentina's most intriguing youth prospects. He normally plays as a marauding [[Full back (association football)|full-back]] who can make forward runs and create chances for his teammates. Barco has also been noted for his versatility, having played as a [[Winger (association football)|winger]].<ref>{{Cite web |first=Jacek |last=Kulig |title=Valentín Barco |url=https://footballtalentscout.net/2021/05/31/valentin-barco/ |website=Football Talent Scout |date=31 May 2021 |access-date=12 January 2024 |archive-date=12 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240112170211/https://footballtalentscout.net/2021/05/31/valentin-barco/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|first=Richard|last=Martin|title=Valentin Barco: Why Man City and Liverpool are targeting the teenage Boca Juniors left-back who moonlights as an attacking playmaker |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/lists/valentin-barco-man-city-teenage-left-back-attacking-playmaker-boca-juniors-argentina/blta2c1ce09e90c9e42 |website=Goal |date=24 November 2023 |access-date=12 January 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Barco: I try to be an all-round full-back |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/articles/valentin-barco-interview-argentina-boca-juniors-u20-world-cup-2023 |website=[[FIFA]] |date=12 January 2024}}</ref>

